'''Christopher Busby''' (born 1 September 1945) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] scientist known for his controversial theories about the negative health effects of very low-dose [[ionising radiation]].
Busby is a director of Green Audit Limited, a private company,<ref name=greenA>[http://www.greenaudit.org Green Audit]</ref> and scientific advisor to the Low Level Radiation Campaign (LLRC) another private company that Busby set up in 1999.<ref>Green Audit, [http://www.greenaudit.org/about_green_audit.htm About Green Audit]</ref> Busby is a visiting professor at the [[University of Ulster]].<ref name=ulster-busby /> Busby was the National Speaker on Science and Technology for the [[Green Party of England and Wales]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/news-archive/874.html |title=Greens launch radiation activist network |publisher=Green Party of England and Wales |date=23 October 2004 |accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/files/reports/2004/Labour%20record%201.htm |title=Far more spin than substance |publisher=Green Party of England and Wales |date=2 September 2002 |accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref>

Following the 2011 [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]], Busby established a television and internet presence where he discussed the risks of [[ionizing radiation]] and the [[Japanese Government|Japanese Government's]] handling of the disaster. Busby furthermore marketed, on his Japanese language website, tests and a mineral supplement (dubbed by critics an "anti-radiation" pill) that he claimed could mitigate the effects of ingested [[Radionuclide|radioisotopes]].<ref name=BusbyPills>{{Cite news| last = Monbiot| first = George| coauthors = Justin McCurry| title = Post-Fukushima 'anti-radiation' pills condemned by scientists| work = The Guardian| accessdate = 2011-11-22| date = 2011-11-21| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2011/nov/21/christopher-busby-radiation-pills-fukushima| location=London}}</ref>

==Career==
Busby obtained a BSc in [[Chemistry]] with [[First Class Honours]] from the [[University of London]], and then worked as a researcher at the [[Wellcome Foundation]] as an analytical chemist{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}. His membership in the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] lapsed in 1984{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}. He later gained a PhD in [[chemical physics]] at the [[University of Kent]], researching [[Raman spectroscopy|Raman spectro-electrochemistry]].<ref name=CERRIE>{{cite web |url=http://www.cerrie.org/people/busby.php |title=Dr Chris Bubsy (CERRIE biography) |publisher=[[Committee Examining Radiation Risks from Internal Emitters]] |accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref> In 1999 Busby stood as an Election Candidate for the European Parliamentary elections.<ref name="1999 Election candidates">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.org.uk/section/1999/1999-election-candidates|title=1999 * Election candidates|work=UK Office of the European Parliament|accessdate=3 April 2011}}</ref> Busby was a member of the British government sponsored [[Committee Examining Radiation Risks from Internal Emitters]] (CERRIE), which operated from 2001 to 2004.<ref name=CERRIE/> In 2001, he was appointed to the UK Ministry of Defence Oversight Committee on Depleted Uranium (DUOB).<ref name=CERRIE/> Between 2003 and 2007 he was a Fellow of the Faculty of Medicine, [[University of Liverpool]], in the Department of Human Anatomy and Cell Biology,<ref name=CERRIE/> and he is currently a visiting professor at the School of Biomedical Sciences, [[University of Ulster]].<ref name=ulster-busby>{{Cite web |url=http://biomed.science.ulster.ac.uk/nsb/Professor-Chris-Busby,31.html |title=Professor Chris Busby |publisher=University of Ulster |accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref>

==Second Event Theory and Photoelectric Effect Controversy==
[[File:Biphasic Curve.gif|320px|thumb|right|''The Biphasic Curve'': The cancer risk vs. radiation level in the low-dose regime (0 to 200 [[Seivert|mSv]]) for '''LNT''' and the {{Font color|red|''' 'Biphasic Curve' '''}} promoted by Busby. {{Font color|green|'''Background'''}} radiation is ~2.4 [[Seivert|mSv]]/year (diagram adapted by Busby from Burlakova ''et al.'' (1998)).<ref name=Burlakova1>{{Cite journal
| issn = 1342-0852
| url = http://www.rri.kyoto-u.ac.jp/NSRG/reports/kr21/kr21pdf/Burlakova.pdf
| issue = 21
| pages = 223–234
| last = Burlakova
| first = E. B.
| coauthors = A. N. Goloshchapov, N. V. Gorbunova, S. M. Gurevich, G. P. Zhizhina, A. I. Kozachenko, A. A. Konradov, D. B. Korman, E. M. Molochkina, L. G. Nagler, others
| title = Peculiarities of Biological Action of Low Irradiation Doses and Their Probable Relation to the Health State of Participants of Chernobyl Accident Liquidation
| journal = Kurri Kr
| year = 1998
}}</ref>]] From 1987 onwards Busby has worked in particular on the health effects of [[ionizing radiation]], developing the 'Second Event Theory' and 'Photoelectric Effect Theory' which distinguishes between hazards from external radiation and internal irradiation from ingested [[Radionuclide|radioisotopes]], upon which he claims the widely accepted [[Linear no-threshold model|linear no-threshold (LNT)]] model substantially underestimates the risk of low level radiation (the [[Linear no-threshold model|LNT]] model is largely constructed from the 1958 to 2001 'Life Span Study' of the 120,321 [[Hibakusha|Japanese Atomic Bomb Survivors]] ({{nihongo|hibakusha|被爆者}}) who were exposed to a powerful ''external'' burst of [[neutron]] and [[Gamma ray|gamma radiation]]).<ref name=Samartzis>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.2106/JBJS.J.00256| pages = JBJS.J.00256| last = Samartzis| first = Dino| coauthors = Nobuo Nishi, Mikiko Hayashi, John Cologne, Harry M. Cullings, Kazunori Kodama, Edward F. Miles, Sachiyo Funamoto, Akihiko Suyama, Midori Soda, Fumiyoshi Kasagi| title = Exposure to Ionizing Radiation and Development of Bone Sarcoma: New Insights Based on Atomic-Bomb Survivors of Hiroshima and Nagasaki| journal = J Bone Joint Surg Am| accessdate = 2011-04-30| date = 2011-03-31| url =  http://jbjs.org/article.aspx?articleID=35498}}</ref> Busby claims that in the low dose regime, radiation moderately above [[Background radiation|background]] causes more cancer than much higher levels of radiation ''i.e.'' a biphasic (bimodal) curve; a claim based on the work of Elena Burlakova.<ref name=Burlakova1/><ref name=Burlakova2>{{Cite book
