| coauthors = Yu. S. Antova, A. N. Goloshchapov, S. M. Gurevich, G. P. Zhizhina, A. I. Kozachenko
| title = Consequences of the Chernobyl Catastrophe on Human Health
| chapter = Mechanisms of biological action of low-dose irradiation
| location = New York, US
| year = 1999
}}</ref>

Busby initially proposed the Second Event Theory (SET) in 1995, in his [[self-published]] book 'Wings of Death: Nuclear Pollution and Human Health'<ref name=BusbyBook>{{Cite book| publisher = Green Audit Books
| isbn = 1-897761-03-1
| last = Busby
| first = Chris
| title = Wings of Death: Nuclear Pollution and Human Health
| date = 1995-10
| url = http://nonuclear.se/busby-wings-of-death
}}</ref> claiming that isotopes which decay sequentially, emitting two or more particles in a short [[decay chain]], have far greater genotoxic effects than predicted by the [[Linear no-threshold model|LNT]] model. In particular, Busby's SET predicts that the [[Strontium 90|<sup>90</sup>Sr-<sup>90</sup>Y]] decay chain might be some ~30 times more carcinogenic than predicted by [[Linear no-threshold model|LNT]], because <!-- according to Busby=superfluous, sentence starting with BUSBY'S --> primary exposure to a beta particle alters a cell to the [[G2 phase|G<sub>2</sub> Phase]], in which <!-- he claims=dito--><!-- A beta-particle, A cell, a phase in which IT is--> it is highly [[Radiosensitivity|radio-sensitive]], and a second particle "hit" within a few hours is more likely to cause [[carcinogenesis]]. 

SET was criticized by Cox & Edwards (2000)<ref name=Cox>{{Cite journal
| issn = 0955-3002
| volume = 76
| issue = 1
| pages = 119–122
| last = Edwards
| first = A A
| coauthors = R Cox
| title = Commentary on the Second Event Theory of Busby
| journal = International Journal of Radiation Biology
| date = 2000-01
| pmid=10665965
| doi = 10.1080/095530000139087
}}</ref> who stated that if Busby's "biologically implausible" theory was correct and ''all'' irradiated cells undergo transformation to the [[G2 phase|G<sub>2</sub> Phase]], it would cause an increased risk factor of just 1.3 times and predict, on the contrary, substantial risk reduction at low doses for single emitting radioisotopes. Furthermore, it was established in 1906 (The Law of Bergonié and Tribondeau) that cells in the [[G2 phase|G<sub>2</sub> Phase]] are more resistant to radiation than cells in the [[Cell_cycle#Mitosis_.28M_Phase.2FMitotic_phase.29|M Phase]] ([[Radiosensitivity]] and [[Cell cycle]]).<ref name=Ribondeau>{{Cite journal
| volume = 143
| pages = 983–985
| last = Ribondeau
| first = L.
| coauthors =  J Bergonié
| title = De quelques résultats de la radiotherapie et essai de fixation d'une technique rationnelle
| journal = Comptes-Rendus de Séances de l'Académie des Sciences
| year = 1906
}}</ref> The [[Committee on Medical Aspects of Radiation in the Environment|Committee Examining Radiation Risks of Internal Emitters]] (CERRIE) report, on which Busby was one of twelve members, exhaustively examined the biological plausibility of SET and commissioned an independent consultant to conduct a literature review. In 2004 CERRIE rejected the SET by a 10 to 2 majority consensus (Busby and non-scientist Richard Bramhall, dissented). The rejection was made for following reasons:<ref name=Goodhead>{{Cite book
| publisher = London: Committee Examining Radiation Risks of Internal Emitters
| isbn = 0-85951-545-1
| last = Goodhead
| first = D.
| coauthors = R. Bramhall, C. Busby, R. Cox, S. Darby, P. Day, J. Harrison, C. Muirhead, P. Roche, J. Simmons, others
| title = Report of the Committee Examining Radiation Risks of Internal Emitters (CERRIE)
| year = 2004
| url = http://www.cerrie.org/pdfs/cerrie_report_e-book.pdf
}}</ref>
 
* The lack of biological plausibility for the basic preconditions of the SET
* The paucity of supporting evidence in the proponents’ reviews of the SET
* The weakness of studies cited in support of the SET
* The absence of supporting evidence found by the independent review commissioned by the Committee

CERRIE also considered and rejected by 10 to 2 consensus the biphasic (bimodal) curve of Burlakova ''et al.'' (1999),<ref name=Burlakova2/> due to the study's "substantial shortcomings"; tables were so ambiguous that the risk-dose response could be interpreted as linear, biphasic or even promoting health ([[radiation hormesis]]).<ref name=Goodhead/>

Busby responded by selling for £25 a 3 person [[minority report]] on his website, which claims that internal low-level radiation is 300 times more dangerous than predicted, the currently accepted [[Linear no-threshold model|LNT]] model is meaningless, and in Sweden and Belarus cancer rates have risen by 40% since Chernobyl.<ref>{{Cite web
| last = Bramhall
| first = Richard
| coauthors = Chris Busby, Paul Dorfman
| title = Committee Examining Radiation Risk of Internal Emitters - MINORITY REPORT
| work = Committee Examining Radiation Risk of Internal Emitters
| date = 2011-07-23
| url = http://www.llrc.org/wobblyscience/subtopic/cerrie.htm
}}</ref>

Later work by Busby focused on the health effects of ingested [[Depleted Uranium]] particles. In particular he proposes that ingested [[Uranium]] particles cause [[photoelectric effect|photoelectric]] enhancement that increases the genotoxic effect of natural background [[Gamma ray|gamma radiation]] by 500 to 1000 times (he claims natural gamma rays strike [[Uranium]] and generate via the photoelectric effect [[secondary electrons]] that damage cells).<ref name=pacifica>[http://www.pacifica.org/programs/dn/030131.html pacifica.org radio], January 31, 2003 interview with Busby, Retrieved 10-02-2008</ref><ref name=bbc>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1422130.stm "Scientist raises new radiation fear"], news.bbc.co.uk, July 5, 2001</ref> Recent work by Busby (2008)<ref name=BusbySchnug>{{Cite book
